<<if .no_atmos_auth>>
## Adopting Atmos Auth for Local Dev (Optional)

This repo does not currently use Atmos Auth. The generated profiles handle CI-side
authentication only; local development continues with your existing mechanism (SSO, static
keys, federated Okta).

To adopt Atmos Auth for local dev later:

1. Add an `auth:` block to `atmos.yaml` with an SSO provider.
2. Keep the `profiles/github-*/` directories — they'll continue to override auth in CI.
3. See <https://atmos.tools/cli/auth/> for the full guide.
<<end>>
## Adding More Orgs

To enable for another org:

1. Add the org's accounts to `profiles/github-plan/atmos.yaml` and `profiles/github-apply/atmos.yaml`.
2. Update `stacks/catalog/aws/iam-role/gha-tf.yaml` with that org's tfstate role ARNs.
3. Add the org's IAM role wildcard patterns to `stacks/catalog/tfstate-backend/defaults.yaml`.
4. Import `mixins/atmos-pro` in the org's `_defaults.yaml`.
5. Deploy the IAM roles and tfstate trust update in each new account.

Or, re-run the skill: `atmos ai ask "add org <name> to atmos pro" --skill atmos-pro`.

## Adding More Repos

To grant a new repository OIDC access to the same AWS accounts:

1. Add the repo to Atmos Pro workspace settings.
2. Add `"<new-org>/<new-repo>:main"` to `trusted_github_repos` in
   `stacks/catalog/aws/iam-role/defaults.yaml`.
3. Redeploy the IAM roles.
4. Create matching auth profiles in the new repo.
5. Copy the four workflow files to the new repo and set its GitHub variables.

